# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-derby
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] Apache Derby is developed as an open source project under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] For a time, Oracle distributed the same binaries under the name **Java DB**.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In June 2015 they announced that for JDK 9 they would no longer be doing so.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In October 2025 Derby developers voted to retire the project and stop supporting it.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] Apache Derby originated at Cloudscape Inc, an Oakland, California, start-up founded in 1996 by Nat Wyatt and Howard Torf to develop Java database technology.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The first release of the database engine, then called JBMS, was in 1997.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] Subsequently, the product was renamed Cloudscape and releases were made about every six months.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In 1999, Informix Software, Inc., acquired Cloudscape, Inc.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In 2001 IBM acquired the database assets of Informix Software, including Cloudscape.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The database engine was re-branded to IBM Cloudscape and releases continued, mainly focusing on embedded use with IBM's Java products and middleware.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In August 2004, IBM contributed the code to the Apache Software Foundation as Derby, an incubator project sponsored by the Apache DB project.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In July 2005 the Derby project graduated from the Apache incubator and is now being developed as a sub-project of the DB Top Level Project at Apache.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] Prior to Derby's graduation from incubation, Sun joined the Derby project with an intent to use Derby as a component in their own products, and with the release of Java 6 in December 2006, Sun started packaging Derby in the JDK branded as Java DB.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] In March 2007, IBM announced that they would withdraw marketing and support for the Cloudscape product, but would continue to contribute to the Apache Derby project.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The Java DB database is Oracle's supported distribution of Apache Derby.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The core of the technology, Derby's database engine, is a full-functioned relational embedded database-engine, supporting JDBC and SQL as programming APIs.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The Derby network server increases the reach of the Derby database engine by providing traditional client server functionality.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The network server allows clients to connect over TCP/IP using the standard DRDA protocol.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] The network server allows the Derby engine to support networked JDBC, ODBC/CLI, Perl.
[src:apache-derby/apache-derby] An embedded database can be configured to act as a hybrid server/embedded RDBMS; to also accept TCP/IP connections from other clients in addition to clients in the same JVM.
[src:apache-derby/derby] Apache Derby, an Apache DB subproject, is an open source relational database implemented entirely in Java and available under the Apache License, Version 2.0.
[src:apache-derby/derby] If you're new to Derby, check out the Quick Start page.
[src:apache-derby/derby] Many ApacheCon presentations that feature Derby can be downloaded from this Derby page.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] An **embedded database** system is a database management system (DBMS) that is tightly integrated with application software, and is embedded within the application rather than provided as a standalone system.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The term “embedded” is sometimes used to refer to use on embedded devices (as opposed to the definition given above).
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] However, only a small subset of embedded database systems are used in real-time embedded systems such as telecommunications switches and consumer electronics.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Advantage Database Server (ADS) is an embedded database management system developed by Sybase.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It provides both Indexed Sequential Access Method (ISAM) and relational data access and is compatible with multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, and Netware.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is available as a royalty-free local file-server database or as a full client-server system.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Apache Derby is an embeddable SQL database engine written entirely in Java.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is fully transactional and supports multi-user access, and is available under the Apache license.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is also distributed as part of Oracle's Java SE Development Kit (JDK) under the name of Java DB.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database was developed by Empress Software, Inc., a privately held company founded in 1979.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is a relational database management system that has been embedded in a range of applications, including medical systems, network routers, nuclear power plant monitors, and satellite management systems.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Empress is an ACID-compliant, SQL database engine with APIs for C, C++, Java, JDBC, ODBC, SQL, ADO.NET, and kernel-level APIs.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Applications developed using these APIs can be run in standalone or client-server modes.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database runs on Linux, Unix, Microsoft Windows, and real-time operating systems.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Extensible Storage Engine (ESE) is an ISAM data storage technology developed by Microsoft.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It serves as a core component of Microsoft Exchange Server and Active Directory, allowing applications to store and retrieve data using indexed and sequential access.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] ESE is also used by Windows Mail and Desktop Search in Windows Vista to store indexes and property information, respectively.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] eXtremeDB, launched by McObject LLC as an in-memory embedded database, was designed specifically for real-time embedded systems.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The initial product was later joined by eXtremeDB High Availability (HA) for fault-tolerant applications.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The eXtremeDB family now includes 64-bit and transaction logging editions, as well as the hybrid eXtremeDB Fusion, which combines in-memory and on-disk data storage.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] In 2008, McObject introduced eXtremeDB Kernel Mode, an embedded DBMS designed to run in an operating system kernel.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] eXtremeDB is used in real-time and embedded systems worldwide.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] McObject also offers Perst, an open source, object-oriented embedded database for Java, Java ME, .NET, .NET Compact Framework, and Silverlight.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded is a relational database engine and an open-source fork of InterBase.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is ACID-compliant, supports triggers and stored procedures, and is available on Linux, macOS, and Windows.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It has the same features as the Classic and SuperServer versions of Firebird.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Starting with Firebird 2.5, two or more threads or applications can access the same database simultaneously.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded acts as a local server for one-threaded client accessing its databases.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] For example, this allows ASP.NET web applications to work properly, because each user runs in a separate thread, so two users can access the same database at the same time without a conflict.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded exports the standard Firebird API entry points.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Unlike SQLite or Access databases, Firebird Embedded databases can be moved to a full Firebird server without modification and are multi-platform, running on Linux and macOS with full ASP.NET Mono support.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Although it can operate within an application process, Firebird is not truly embedded because it cannot be statically linked.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] H2 is an open-source database engine written in Java.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It supports both embedded and server modes, as well as clustering, and can run within the Google App Engine environment.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It supports encrypted database files using AES or XTEA.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Development of H2 began in May 2004, and it was first published on December 14, 2005.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] H2 is dual-licensed and is available under a modified version of the Mozilla Public License (MPL) or the unmodified Eclipse Public License (EPL) 1.0.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] HailDB is a standalone, embeddable form of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Because it is based on the same codebase as InnoDB, it includes many of the same features, such as high performance and scalability, multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), row-level locking, deadlock detection, fault tolerance, and automatic crash recovery.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] As an embedded engine independent of MySQL, HailDB does not include server components such as networking or object-level permissions.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] By eliminating MySQL server overhead, it has a relatively small footprint and is well suited for embedding in applications that require high performance and concurrency.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] As with many embedded database systems, HailDB is designed to be accessed primarily through an ISAM-like C API rather than SQL, although a limited SQL variant is supported.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The project is no longer maintained as of 2015.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] HSQLDB is an open-source relational database management system with a BSD-like license that runs within the same Java Virtual Machine as the embedded application.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It supports a variety of in-memory and disk-based table modes, Unicode, and SQL:2016.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] InfinityDB is a sorted, hierarchical key-value store.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is available in encrypted and client-server editions.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The database provides transactional support, data compression, and operates within a single file, enabling simplified deployment and minimal administration.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] APIs include the ItemSpace interface, a ConcurrentNavigableMap view, and support for JSON.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The RemoteItemSpace component can redirect embedded API calls to other database instances.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The client-server edition includes a lightweight servlet server, web-based administration and database browsing tools, and REST support for Python.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Informix Dynamic Server (IDS) is an enterprise-class, embeddable database server that combines features such as low footprint, programmability, and autonomic capabilities with enterprise database features including high availability and flexible replication.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] IDS is used in embedded scenarios such as IP telephony call-processing systems, point-of-sale applications, and financial transaction processing systems.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] InterBase is a cross-platform, Unicode-enabled SQL database that can be embedded within turn-key applications.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It supports symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), on-disk AES-256 encryption, SQL-92 compliance, and ACID properties, and is available on Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, iOS, and Android platforms.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] InterBase is used in both small- to medium-sized and large enterprise environments, supporting multi-user and mobile application development.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] *InterBase Light* is a free version designed for mobile devices and is suitable for mobile applications.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Organizations can upgrade to a paid version as requirements for features such as change management and security increase.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] InterBase has been adopted in industries including defense, airspace, oil and gas, and manufacturing.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Kùzu is an embeddable graph database management system that supports the Cypher query language.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It implements a range of existing and novel state-of-art storage, indexing, and query processing techniques to support the management and querying of large graphs.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Kùzu achieves its performance through a combination of join algorithms, including binary and worst-case optimal joins, as well as factorization and vectorized query execution on a columnar storage layer, along with compression and parallelization techniques common in modern database systems.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Kùzu is developed and maintained by Kùzu Inc., a startup based in Waterloo, Ontario, Canada, and is available as open-source software under the MIT license.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] LevelDB is an ordered key-value store created by Google as a compact implementation of the Bigtable storage design.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is provided as a library, with a native API in C++.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It also includes official C wrappers for most functionality, and third-party wrappers are available for languages such as Python, PHP, Go, Node.js, and Objective C.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Google distributes LevelDB under the New BSD License.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB) is a memory-mapped key-value database developed for the OpenLDAP Project.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is written in C, and its API is modeled after the Berkeley DB API, but simplified.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The library is compact, typically compiling to under 40 KB of x86 object code.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] LMDB implements B+ trees with multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), a single-level store, copy-on-write, and provides full ACID transactions without deadlocks.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is optimized for high read concurrency: readers require no locks, readers do not block writers, and writers do not block readers, allowing read performance to scale linearly across multiple threads and CPUs.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Third-party wrappers are available for C++, Erlang and Python.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] LMDB is distributed under the OpenLDAP Public License.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] As of 2013, the OpenLDAP Project has deprecated the use of Berkeley DB in favor of LMDB.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Mimer SQL is a proprietary relational database server.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] An embedded, zero-maintenance version is available, featuring a small footprint due to its modular design, full support for the SQL standard, and ports to Windows, Linux, Automotive Grade Linux, Android, QNX, INTEGRITY, and other platforms.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] MonetDB/e is the embedded version of the open-source MonetDB SQL column store engine.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is available for C, C++, Java (JDBC), and Python, and is distributed under the MonetDB License, based on MPL 2.0.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Its predecessor, MonetDBLite (for R, Python, and Java), is no longer maintained and has been replaced by MonetDB/e.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The Embedded MySQL Server Library provides most of the features of the standard MySQL server as a linkable library that runs within the context of a client process.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] After initialization, clients can use the same C API calls as when communicating with a separate MySQL server, but with lower communication overhead and without the need for a separate database process.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] NexusDB is the commercial successor to the FlashFiler database, which is now open source.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Both databases can be embedded in Delphi applications to create stand-alone executables with full database functionality.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] ObjectDB is an object database for Java that can be used in either client-server mode or embedded (in process) mode.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Oracle's embedded database is Berkeley DB, which Oracle acquired from Sleepycat Software.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Berkeley DB was originally developed at the University of California.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is a fast, open-source embedded database and is used in several well-known open-source products, including the Linux and BSD Unix operating systems, the Apache Web server, and the OpenOffice productivity suite.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] In recent years, some projects have switched to using Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB), citing better performance in key scenarios and a simpler "less is more" design, as well as changes to Berkeley DB's licensing.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] RocksDB was created by Facebook as a fork of LevelDB.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It focuses on performance, particularly on solid-state drives (SSDs), and adds a range of features, including transactions, backups, snapshots, bloom filters, column families, expiry, custom merge operators, more tunable compaction, statistics collection, and geospatial indexing.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is used as a storage engine inside of several other databases, including ArangoDB, Ceph, CockroachDB, MyRocks, Rocksandra, TiKV, and YugabyteDB.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] solid DB is a hybrid on-disk/in-memory, relational database often used as an embedded system database in telecommunications equipment, network software, and similar applications.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] Its in-memory technology enables throughput of tens of thousands of transactions per second with response times measured in microseconds.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] A high-availability option maintains two synchronized copies of the data.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] In the event of a system failure, applications can recover access to solidDB in less than a second without data loss.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] SQLite is a software library that provides a self-contained, serverless, zero-configuration, transactional SQL database engine.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is the most widely deployed SQL database engine in the world.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The source code, written primarily in C, is in the public domain.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] SQLite includes both a native C library and a simple command-line client for managing its database.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It is included in several operating systems, including Android, FreeBSD, iOS, macOS, and Windows 10, and is also used by the Chromium web browser and its derivatives.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact is an embedded database by Microsoft with features including multi-process connections, T-SQL, ADO.NET Sync Services for synchronizing with back-end databases, Merge Replication with SQL Server, and programming APIs such as LINQ to SQL, LINQ to Entities, and ADO.NET.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] The product runs on both desktop and mobile Windows platforms.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] It has been in production software over a long period.
[src:apache-derby/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact has undergone multiple rebrandings and has been known by various names, including SQL CE, SQL Server CE, SQL Server Mobile, and SQL Mobile.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:apache-derby/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
